  "response_text": "The average weekly consumption of whole milk per agent begins at a high level of 2654.81 units at the initial time step and exhibits a consistent and substantial decline over the simulation period. By the final recorded time step, consumption drops to a minimum value of 253.10 units, representing a reduction of approximately 90% from the starting point. 

The trajectory shows a distinct pattern of rapid decline during the early phases. Between the first five time steps, the metric decreases sharply, with statistical analysis confirming a significant downward trend (slope ≈ -139.18). This steep descent continues through the subsequent five steps, where the rate of decline intensifies to a slope of approximately -221.11. While the decline remains negative, the rate moderates in the middle phases of the simulation, fluctuating between slopes of -38.13 and -23.28, before becoming statistically non-significant in the 15 to 19 time step window. 

Towards the latter stages, the downward momentum resumes. Significant decreasing trends are observed again between time steps 20 and 24 (slope ≈ -17.45). After a brief period of statistical stagnation, the consumption metric experiences its final major drop, falling below 400 units by the 30th time step. The data indicates specific inflection points at steps 5, 13, 16, 19, 24, 25, 27, and 30, reflecting periods of acceleration in the adoption of alternatives or shifts in the rate of habit erosion among the consumer agents. No increasing trends or oscillations were observed; the dynamic is defined by a persistent, multi-phase reduction in whole milk preference."
}

